ely B.C. response in the event of a "yes" vote in any future Quebec referendum on sovereignty. Clearly written and provocative, The Politics of Resentment provides a new way of thinking about British Columbia's place within the Canadian federation. It draws on a wide range of sources - from government documents and from the media, to the work of B.C. authors and commentators, to the academic literature on regionalism and nationalism - to capture what underlies the often fractured relationship between Canada's westernmost province and the rest of the country.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFederal governmentzCanadaxPublic opinion. 0aRegionalismzBritish ColumbiaxPublic opinion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Nationalism & Patriotism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485076640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850766423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850766/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles